# SwiftUI UI Design Rules:

Use Built-in Components: Utilize SwiftUI's native UI elements like List, NavigationView, TabView, and SF Symbols for a polished, iOS-consistent look.

Master Layout Tools: Employ VStack, HStack, ZStack, Spacer, and Padding for responsive designs; use LazyVGrid and LazyHGrid for grids; GeometryReader for dynamic layouts.

Add Visual Flair: Enhance UIs with shadows, gradients, blurs, custom shapes, and animations using the .animation() modifier for smooth transitions.

Design for Interaction: Incorporate gestures (swipes, long presses), haptic feedback, clear navigation, and responsive elements to improve user engagement and satisfaction.

# Application overview:

You are building a productivity app called Deliberate.
The app uses the Screen Time API to block the user's accessing applications.

We are using SwiftData.

During the onboarding the user would take a picture of an object to calculate and store its feature print. Then the app main screen has a small camera square in the center that uses the Vision API to compute the distance of the image from the one done in the onboarding and display it as text. 

Later the user would be able to start the blocking process if the image similarity is above a certain threshold. If the app is already blocking, the successful picture with a close enough image stops the blocking process. 

Under the small camera square, there is a button that allows the user to select and customize a profile that define the applications to block.

At the top right of the application there is a button that allows the user to access the settings.

At the bottom of the  main page there is a counter that shows the total time spent while the application blocks the user's accessing applications.

The app has an onboarding step to ask for permissions to use the Screen Time API.

